    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-10-01T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-10-01T10:00:00-05:00" n="787"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d787">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/651: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-10-01T18:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 1, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 1—4:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1742. For the President from Harriman. Beaverbrook and I came to an understanding
                    with Stalin last night. A memorandum covering our understanding has been agreed
                    to by the members of your mission and all others concerned.<note n="96"
                        xml:id="d787fn96">See telegram No. 1753, October 3, 6 p.m., from the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union, <ref target="#pg_841">p. 841</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0852" n="840" xml:id="pg_840"/>
                <p>Our part of the agreement is to make available to the Soviet Government supplies
                    within the list of materials which we have been authorized to offer.</p>
                <p>We have agreed in addition to consider sympathetically a long list of additional
                    raw materials which as to types and quantities seem to us to be reasonable in
                    most cases and which we will recommend be added. On transportation we made no
                    commitment but have offered to help.</p>
                <p>Beaverbrook for the British has made enormous sacrifices.</p>
                <p>We have closed the conference today in an atmosphere of great enthusiasm by all
                    who participated.<note n="97" xml:id="d787fn97">The address made by W. Averell
                        Harriman at the close of the conference, as translated from the Russian
                        press release, is printed in Department of State <hi rend="italic"
                            >Bulletin</hi>, November 8, 1941, p. 364.</note> Stalin personally is
                    much gratified and sends you his personal thanks.</p>
                <p>Steinhardt has been most helpful and joins me in sending you affectionate
                    regards. [Harriman.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
